<P>Why is OOXML a bad standard? What does it mean for open source =
developers?=20
And what, if anything, can menbers of the open source community do, now =
that=20
OOXML has been adopted by the ISO?</P>
<P><A title=3Dcontinue name=3Dcontinue></A>We love to talk about "open =
standards" in=20
the computer industry. But how do such standards get created? The story =
of=20
OOXML, officially accepted as of today by the <A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO">ISO</A>, is a cautionary =
tale.</P>
<P>The story begins several years ago, when Microsoft switched to XML =
file=20
formats for its Office products. Partly as a response to the =
standardization of=20
OpenOffice's file format (<A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenDocument">ODF</A>) Microsoft =
submitted=20
its XML document formats, known as <A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OOXML">"Office Open XML,"</A> or <A =

href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OOXML">"OOXML,"</A> to <A=20
href=3D"http://www.ecma-international.org/">Ecma International</A>, a =
European=20
standards body for the computer industry, and was granted the standard =
(<A=20
href=3D"http://www.ecma-international.org/publications/standards/Ecma-376=
.htm">Ecma-376</A>)=20
in December 2006. A revised version of Ecma-376 was officially adopted =
by ISO,=20
the International Standards Organization, earlier today (April 2nd, =
2008),=20
making OOXML an official international standard.</P>
<P>There are a number of standards bodies in the world, and each has its =
own set=20
of rules. In general, a standards body appoints a committee to review =
and=20
approve a particular standard. That committee reviews the draft, gathers =

comments and evidence, and revises the draft in the wake of comments, =
often=20
multiple times. This process can take an awfully long time, both because =
the=20
committee members are volunteers, and because a standard is something so =

complex, whose effects will be felt for decades to come.</P>
<P>The members of a standardization committee obviously worry about =
whether a=20
standard is technically correct. They try to remove inconsistencies -- =
both=20
internal and with the outside world -- and to ensure that the standard =
is as=20
well defined and accurate as possible.</P>
<P>Committees must also consider how easy it will be to implement the =
standard.=20
A standard that can only be implemented by its author is no standard at =
all. <A=20
href=3D"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FTP">FTP</A>, a file-transfer =
protocol and=20
standard, has been around for more than 20 years, and is only meant to =
transfer=20
files from one computer to another. Despite this, there are still =
problems=20
getting FTP clients and servers to communicate seamlessly. The simpler =
the=20
standard, the better it is for implementers and end users alike.</P>
<P>Another consideration has to do with intellectual property: Even if =
it's=20
technically possible for everyone to implement a particular standard, it =
should=20
be legally possible, as well. That is, implementation of the standard =
should not=20
require the licensing of technologies from anyone else, particularly =
another=20
member of the committee. The W3C itself was embroiled in such a dispute =
several=20
years ago, when it considered the appropriateness of standards that =
included=20
patents, after a number of companies pushed for such a =
consideration.</P>
<P>Unfortunately, yesterday's adoption of OOXML as an ISO standard fails =
on all=20
three counts. To begin with, it seems that the OOXML standard was <A=20
href=3D"http://holloway.co.nz/can-other-vendors-implement-ooxml.html">poo=
rly=20
defined</A>, leaving a huge number of ambiguities and undefined terms. =
That's=20
not surprising, given the fact that it is <A=20
href=3D"http://clipmarks.com/clipmark/9AEAAFE4-9801-40AD-AF27-7591BEB16DB=
3/">6,000=20
-- yes, six <EM>thousand</EM> -- pages</A> long, a size which makes it =
nearly=20
impossible to ensure internal consistency. The large size also ensures =
that it=20
will be difficult to create alternative implementations; would you like =
to be=20
the programmer charged with checking that a particular program adheres =
to all=20
6,000 pages of the standard?</P>
<P>Moreover, parts of the standard require a programmer to deviate from =
many=20
other, correct standards. For example, 1900 was not a leap year, as is =
the case=20
with three out of every four "00" years. (Thus, 1900 was not a leap =
year, but=20
2000 was.) Microsoft got this point wrong when they first implemented =
Excel, and=20
as a result, the OOXML standard requires that implementers make this =
same error,=20
for the sake of consistency.</P>
<P>There are also serious questions regarding some Microsoft patents =
that any=20
implementer will need to use. Microsoft has promised that it will not =
sue OOXML=20
implementers for patent infringement, but the <A=20
href=3D"http://www.groklaw.net/article.php?story=3D20070123071154671#Pate=
nt_rights_to_implement_the_Ecma_376_specification_have_not_been_granted">=
Groklaw=20
site points out that this statement might be meaningless</A>.</P>
<P>A Wiki document listing problems that people have found with OOXML =
are=20
located <A =
href=3D"http://www.grokdoc.net/index.php/EOOXML_objections">on this=20
site</A>. There are many other objections to be found on the Web, such =
as <A=20
href=3D"http://cytrap.eu/blog/?p=3D129">here</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://www.tbray.org/ongoing/When/200x/2007/01/24/Mixup">here</A>=
, and <A=20
href=3D"http://www.noooxml.org/forum/t-16529/ooxml-problems-in-75-slides"=
>here</A>.</P>
<P>If anyone in the open-source community were to propose a huge,=20
unimplementable standard, they would have been laughed out of town. So =
this=20
raises at least two questions: How did this happen, and what do we do =
about=20
it?</P>
<P>This happened, from everything I can tell, through old-fashioned =
politics:=20
Microsoft, from numerous reports I've read, managed to get a number of =
countries=20
to vote in favor of adopting OOXML. For example, Norway's ISO =
representative=20
voted to approve OOXML, despite the <A=20
href=3D"http://www.informationweek.com/windows/showArticle.jhtml?articleI=
D=3D207001016">vocal=20
objection of the Norwegian standards committee</A>. Politics are a =
normal part=20
of the standardization landscape, but this seems to have been an extreme =
case,=20
by everyone's measure.</P>
<P>The adoption of OOXML is troubling not only from the perspective of =
open=20
standards, but open source software as well. A 6,000-page standard is =
going to=20
be difficult, if not impossible, to implement, which means that =
Microsoft has=20
seemingly received international approval for a monopoly on its file =
formats. <A=20
href=3D"http://www.openoffice.org/">Open Office</A> and other =
open-source programs=20
can claim that ODF is "more open" than OOXML, but that's an argument =
which will=20
be difficult to make to people without a technical background.</P>
<P>I must admit that it's not obvious what we, in the open source =
community, can=20
do about this. Lobbying your national standards organization might have =
some=20
effect, but probably not. Trying to use ODF and other open standards =
sounds fine=20
in practice, but will quickly run up against the reality, which is that =
most=20
people use MS Office. And encouraging third-party software developers to =
work=20
with ODF before OOXML would probably be suicidal for a business, given =
the=20
immense numbers of MS Office users, especially when compared with=20
OpenOffice.</P>
<P>So, I ask you, our readers: What can and should we do about this, now =
that=20
the decision has been made?</P>
